  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Federal contract obligations in Tennessee through FY2026 to date totaled $9.7B, with 15,680 awards and an average award size of $618K. Obligations fell 11.6% year over year. Historical annual totals show variation: FY21 was $10.8B, FY22 was $11.4B, FY23 was $11.2B, FY24 was $10.8B, FY25 was $11B, and FY26 is $9.7B to date. Spending in FY2026 to date concentrates heavily in Facilities Support Services at $5.4B and in a small group of vendors: CONSOLIDATED NUCLEAR SECURITY, LLC received $2.9B and UT-BATTELLE LLC received $2.4B. The Department of Energy is the single largest buyer at $6.3B, followed by the Department of Defense at $1.3B and the Department of Justice at $701M. Other notable industries include Remediation Services at $611M, Security Guards and Patrol Services at $597M, and Engineering Services at $564M. The FY2026 to date totals are partial for the fiscal year.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How has Tennessee's federal contracting trended recently?",
        "body": "Obligations were $9.7B in FY26 to date, down 11.6% year over year. Annual totals have ranged from $10.8B to $11.4B in prior years, with FY21 at $10.8B, FY22 at $11.4B, FY23 at $11.2B, FY24 at $10.8B, and FY25 at $11B. The FY2026 to date total is a partial fiscal-year figure."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Which agencies and vendors dominate Tennessee federal spending?",
        "body": "The Department of Energy accounted for $6.3B of obligations, making it the largest buying agency, followed by the Department of Defense at $1.3B and the Department of Justice at $701M. CONSOLIDATED NUCLEAR SECURITY, LLC received $2.9B and UT-BATTELLE LLC received $2.4B, while Facilities Support Services totaled $5.4B among industries."
      }
    ]
